{{distinguish|Barasana language}} {{Infobox language |name=Waimajã |nativename=Bará |states=[[Colombia]], [[Brazil]] |region= |ethnicity= |speakers={{sigfig|539|1}}<!--data supports only 1 sig fig--> |date=2004–2006 |ref=e18 |speakers2=some monolinguals over age 40 (2004?)<ref name=e15>{{e17|bao}}</ref><!--both figs 1st appear here, so may be from same source--> |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Tucanoan languages|Tucanoan]] |fam2=Eastern |fam3=Central |fam4=Bara |iso3=bao |lc1=pok|ld1=Pokangá (Bará) |glotto=waim1255 |glottorefname=Waimaha }}
'''Waimajã''' (Waimaha), generically known as '''Bará''' or (Northern) '''Barasano''', is a [[Tucanoan languages|Tucanoan language]] of [[Colombia]] and [[Brazil]]. As of 1971, the population of speakers generally lived along the [[List of rivers of Colombia|rivers of Columbia]], namely, Colorado, Yapu, Inambu, Macucu, and Tiquie.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stolte|first=Joel and Nancy|year=1971|title=A DESCRIPTION OF NORTHERN BARASANO PHONOLOGY|url=https://doi.org/10.1515/ling.1971.9.75.86|journal=Linguistics|language=en|volume=9|issue=75|pages=86–92|doi=10.1515/ling.1971.9.75.86|issn=1613-396X|via=De Gruyter}}</ref>
